# Starting a New Project

When creating a new add-on from this boilerplate, update the items below.
Use find-and-replace where noted; the rest are one-off edits.

---

## 1. Pick your identifiers

Decide these up front — they propagate everywhere:

| Identifier | Example | Used in |
|---|---|---|
| **Project name** | `My Smart Lights` | UI, README, logs |
| **Slug** | `my_smart_lights` | config.yaml, HA registry |
| **npm scope** | `@smart-lights` | all package.json, Dockerfile, tsconfig, imports |
| **npm name** | `smart-lights-addon` | root package.json, Docker image tag |
| **Panel icon** | `mdi:lightbulb` | config.yaml |

---

## 2. Global find-and-replace

Run these across the entire project:

| Find | Replace with | Affects |
|---|---|---|
| `ha-addon-boilerplate` | `your-npm-name` | root package.json, .vscode/tasks.json (Docker image tag) |
| `ha_addon_boilerplate` | `your_slug` | config.yaml |
| `HA Add-on Boilerplate` | `Your Project Name` | config.yaml, index.html, App.tsx, run.sh, devcontainer.json, cursor rules |
| `Home Assistant Add-on Boilerplate` | `Your Project Name` | App.tsx footer, README.md |

After replacing, run `pnpm install` to regenerate the lockfile.

---

## 3. One-off edits

### config.yaml
- `description` — one-line add-on description
- `panel_icon` — MDI icon name (browse at https://pictogrammers.com/library/mdi/)
- `panel_title` — short title shown in HA sidebar
- `options` / `schema` — add your add-on's config fields

### repository.yaml
- `name` — repository display name
- `url` — your GitHub repo URL
- `maintainer` — your name and email

### README.md
- Rewrite to describe your add-on

### client/index.html
- `<title>` — browser tab title

### client/public/favicon.svg
- Replace with your own icon (SVG recommended)

### client/src/App.tsx
- Header title
- Footer text

### client/src/pages/Dashboard/index.tsx
- Subtitle and info card content — describe your add-on instead of the boilerplate

### client/vite.config.ts
- Fallback version string (`'0.1.0'`) — optional, auto-set by `ADDON_VERSION` env

### .devcontainer/devcontainer.json
- `name` — dev container display name
- `forwardPorts` — adjust if your server uses different ports

### .cursor/rules/project-overview.mdc
- Rewrite to describe your add-on's purpose and stack

---

## 4. Database (optional)

If your add-on needs persistence:

1. Set `DATABASE_URL` in `server/.env` (SQLite is the zero-config default)
2. Edit `server/prisma/schema.prisma` — add your models
3. Run `pnpm --filter @your-scope/server db:migrate` to create the first migration
4. To switch to PostgreSQL: change `provider` to `"postgresql"`, update column types, set a PG connection string

If your add-on does NOT need a database, no action needed — the server runs fine without one.

---

## 5. After setup

- [ ] `pnpm install` — regenerate lockfile with new package names
- [ ] `pnpm prisma:generate` — regenerate Prisma client (if using DB)
- [ ] `pnpm build` — verify production build
